Hey Lila,

I just got back from a 5-week roadtrip around the country with my
family (including a row full of kids in the back seat =F0=9F=99=88). We
mostly visited family and friends, but I also hosted a few
meetups around the nation =E2=80=93 and it was wonderful getting to talk
with many of you about design and the industry.

Also gave a guest lecture at my alma mater, Olin College =F0=9F=99=8C
One topic that came up again and again was: making a good
portfolio.

I=E2=80=99ve already written 4,000 words on this (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/mvuk39g92xf5hl32l5fm/08hwh9hmg64kwvtl/aHR=
0cHM6Ly9sZWFybnVpLmRlc2lnbi9ibG9nL2hvdy1jcmVhdGUtdXgtdWktcG9ydGZvbGlvLXdpdG=
hvdXQtbXVjaC1leHBlcmllbmNlLmh0bWw=3D
), but today, I want to emphasize a different lesson on creating
a portfolio in 2021:

There are now SO MANY bootcamps churning out designers that one
of your MAIN PORTFOLIO GOALS is to AVOID looking like a typical
bootcamp grad.

You know what I'm talking about. I=E2=80=99m sure you=E2=80=99ve seen =E2=
=80=9Cthe look=E2=80=9D:

=E2=80=8B
This above-the-fold section is just tremendously average:

* Overused font (Open Sans)
* Overused color for this type of design (blue)
* Big intro sentence with salutation, name, position =E2=80=93 just like
so many other portfolios
* No attention to detail (selected =E2=80=9CWork=E2=80=9D is lighter (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/mvuk39g92xf5hl32l5fm/l2hehmho6mpzv9b6/aHR=
0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9lcmlrZGtlbm5lZHkvc3RhdHVzLzEzMjg3NzE1OTc3ODg3OTg5Nz=
c=3D
) the non-selected items; social icons are pitch black (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/mvuk39g92xf5hl32l5fm/z2hghnhop2z8rgcp/aHR=
0cHM6Ly9pYW5zdG9ybXRheWxvci5jb20vZGVzaWduLXRpcC1uZXZlci11c2UtYmxhY2sv
))

So how do you think outside the box?

My best advice: make something hard to re-create in Figma.

In my opinion, if you really want your portfolio to stand out
from the others, you should include some visuals that require an
app besides Figma/Sketch to create: e.g. Photoshop, 3D, pixel
art, animation, WebGL, etc.

To test this, I signed up for Devon Ko=E2=80=99s highly respected =E2=80=9C=
3D for
Designers (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/mvuk39g92xf5hl32l5fm/x0hph6hn9vmllrt5/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuM2Rmb3JkZXNpZ25lcnMuY29tLw=3D=3D
)=E2=80=9D course.

(
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/mvuk39g92xf5hl32l5fm/x0hph6hn9vmllrt5/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuM2Rmb3JkZXNpZ25lcnMuY29tLw=3D=3D
)=E2=80=8B
It was actually really awesome. Devon is a hilarious =E2=80=93 and
effective =E2=80=93 teacher. Within 2.5 hours, I had already made this
(and, to be clear, I was going slow and tinkering):

=E2=80=8B
Mr. Flappy Flag may not look like much, but slap him in the
middle of a portfolio site...

=E2=80=8B
And that=E2=80=99s a huge improvement! Like, sheets-in-the-breeze may not
be your exact cup of tea, but ask any design recruiter which
portfolio is more promising/interesting/intriguing, and you're
gonna get one answer.

Now this ain't the only thing to making a good portfolio =E2=80=93 not by
a longshot. But if you're trying to get things started on the
right foot, look beyond Figma for out-of-the-box visuals =E2=80=93
whether that's 3D, top-notch Photoshopping, beautiful animations,
or mesmerizing WebGL, etc. =F0=9F=91=8D

Cheers,Erik D. Kennedy

PS. This is perhaps the most important and serious postscript
I=E2=80=99ve ever written, but the teacher of 3D for Designers, Devon Ko,
has been on kidney dialysis for over 2 and a half years. Unless
Devon can find a kidney donor in the near future, she will die.

=E2=80=A6which would be a shame, because she=E2=80=99s awesome =F0=9F=99=82

If you have type O blood, live in the US, and are between 18 and
65, you can apply to donate (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/mvuk39g92xf5hl32l5fm/kkhmh6h860p33ebl/aHR=
0cHM6Ly9raWRuZXlmb3JkZXZvbi5jb20v
) a kidney to Devon.

Donating a kidney doesn=E2=80=99t lower your own life expectancy. It=E2=80=
=99s
also free (which, uh, says something about our medical system
that I even have to mention that).

And I=E2=80=99m not trying to downplay it here =E2=80=93 it=E2=80=99s still=
 a huge deal
to part with one of your perfectly good organs. But the docs do
some extensive screening to make sure the donor is going to be
totally healthy with one kidney.

You can read Devon's full story here (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/mvuk39g92xf5hl32l5fm/kkhmh6h860p33ebl/aHR=
0cHM6Ly9raWRuZXlmb3JkZXZvbi5jb20v
). Actually fun fact: the favicon for the site is a smiling,
waving cartoon kidney, which gives you a sense of Devon's way of
doing things =E2=80=93 up to and including facing her own mortality.

(May we all have the strength of mind to face death in the eye
and make cutesy favicons =F0=9F=92=AA)

